Digital Rectal Exam
A digital rectal exam (DRE) is an important exam for diagnosis, staging, and follow-up. It involves inserting a gloved, lubricated finger into the anus and rectum to detect or assess growths or other abnormalities in the anal canal and nearby areas.

High-Resolution Anoscopy
High-resolution anoscopy (HRA) is a procedure that allows a health care provider to view and examine the anal canal with magnification. After a numbing gel is applied to the anal area, a short, hollow tool (an anoscope) is inserted a few inches into the anus. Next, a liquid called acetic acid is applied to the anal canal tissue. A special magnifying glass called a colposcope is then used to closely examine the tissues of the anal canal.

Well differentiated
Well-differentiated cancer cells are those that have a clear and distinct appearance, indicating a lower grade of malignancy.

Moderately differentiated
Moderately-differentiated cancer cells have a more mixed appearance, indicating an intermediate grade of malignancy.

Poorly differentiated
Poorly-differentiated cancer cells have a disorganized and irregular appearance, indicating a high grade of malignancy.

Undifferentiated
Undifferentiated cancer cells have a highly disorganized and irregular appearance, indicating a high grade of malignancy.

Local excision
Local excision is a surgical procedure that involves removing a small area of tissue, including the cancerous lesion, from the body.

Surgical margin
The surgical margin is the area of tissue surrounding the cancerous lesion that is removed during surgery.

1 cm
1 cm is a unit of measurement used to describe the size of the surgical margin

National Comprehensive Cancer Network
The National Comprehensive Cancer Network is a non-profit organization that provides guidelines for cancer care.

AML
AML stands for Acute Myeloid Leukemia, a type of blood cancer.

bone marrow
Bone marrow is the soft, spongy tissue found in the center of most bones.

plasma
Plasma is the liquid component of blood, made up of mostly water.

red blood cells
Red blood cells are the cells in the blood that carry oxygen throughout the body.

white blood cells
White blood cells are the cells in the blood that fight infections.

platelets
Platelets are the cells in the blood that help control bleeding.

hematopoietic stem cells
Hematopoietic stem cells are the early blood-forming cells that develop into blood cells.

RUNX1::RUNX1T
RUNX1::RUNX1T is a genetic mutation associated with leukemia predisposition syndromes.

Leukemia Predisposition Syndromes
Leukemia predisposition syndromes are hereditary conditions that increase the risk of developing leukemia.

Hereditary Cancer Syndromes
Hereditary cancer syndromes are genetic conditions that increase the risk of developing certain types of cancer.

Family History of Leukemia
A family history of leukemia can affect treatment decisions and genetic testing.

Skin Punch Biopsy
A skin punch biopsy is a procedure used to obtain DNA from skin and connective tissue to test for genetic predisposition to leukemia.

Punch Biopsy
A punch biopsy is a procedure used to obtain tissue samples for genetic testing.<SEP>A punch biopsy is a procedure used to obtain tissue samples for genetic testing

CT or PET/MRI
CT or PET/MRI is a type of medical imaging equipment used to diagnose and monitor various conditions, including cancer.

natural language processing
Natural language processing is a field of computer science and artificial intelligence that focuses on the interaction between computers and humans using natural language.

scales
Scales are instruments used for weighing or measuring the mass of objects, often used in medical and scientific contexts.

biochemical tests
Biochemical tests are laboratory tests that analyze the chemical composition of bodily fluids, such as blood, urine, and saliva, to diagnose or monitor various diseases.

melanoma
Melanoma is a type of skin cancer that begins in the melanocytes, the cells responsible for producing skin color.

cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma
Cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma is a type of skin cancer that affects the squamous cells in the epidermis.

NCCN Guidelines for Patients
NCCN Guidelines for Patients are a set of guidelines for patients with specific types of cancer, providing information on diagnosis, treatment, and management.

Breast Cancer
Breast cancer is a type of cancer that starts in the cells of the breast.

Ductal Carcinoma
Ductal carcinoma is a type of breast cancer that starts in the cells that line the milk ducts.

Lobular Carcinoma
Lobular carcinoma is a type of breast cancer that starts in the lobules (milk glands) of the breast.

Breast Cancer Screening
Breast cancer screening is the process of detecting breast cancer at its earliest stages, often through imaging tests or clinical exams.

Mammogram
Mammogram is a type of imaging test used to examine the breast, often as part of breast cancer screening.

Cancer
Cancer is a disease characterized by the abnormal growth and spread of cells in the body.

Infraclavicular Nodes
Infraclavicular nodes are lymph nodes located in the armpit area, near the clavicle.

MRI
MRI is a medical imaging technique that uses radio waves and powerful magnets to create detailed images of the body's internal structures, including the brain and spinal cord.

CT
CT (computed tomography) is a medical imaging technique that uses x-rays to create cross-sectional images of the body, including the brain and spinal cord.

MRI of the brain
MRI of the brain is a specific type of MRI scan that focuses on the brain, providing detailed images of its structures and any abnormalities.

Stereotactic biopsy
Stereotactic biopsy is a surgical procedure that uses a computerized navigation system to guide the removal of a small sample of tissue from the brain, typically for the diagnosis of primary CNS lymphoma.

Primary CNS lymphoma
Primary CNS lymphoma is a type of cancer that affects the central nervous system, specifically the brain and spinal cord.
